00:21:01.730 --> 00:21:03.040
know about the flying one.

00:21:03.040 --> 00:21:05.530
But I still feel like, if I look
at the most popular games

00:21:05.530 --> 00:21:07.710
on the Web, if I go to
Kongregate and see what's

00:21:07.710 --> 00:21:11.130
driving a lot of the online
games right now, it's still

00:21:11.130 --> 00:21:12.250
primarily Flash.

00:21:12.250 --> 00:21:14.780
Some Unity, and you know,
HTML5 is there.

00:21:14.780 --> 00:21:20.120
But it hasn't becomes the
dominant force yet, in games

00:21:20.120 --> 00:21:21.350
in the browser.

00:21:21.350 --> 00:21:22.951
Why not?

00:21:22.951 --> 00:21:23.850
I'm asking you.

00:21:23.850 --> 00:21:24.730
COLT McANLIS: That's
fine, that's fine.

00:21:24.730 --> 00:21:27.500
So I think you bring up a very
good point about sort of,

00:21:27.500 --> 00:21:29.070
where is the evolution
of HTML5.

00:21:29.070 --> 00:21:30.790
And I want to approach
this from a long

00:21:30.790 --> 00:21:32.550
view perspective first.

00:21:32.550 --> 00:21:36.170
So first off, when HTML5 was
first announced and what it

00:21:36.170 --> 00:21:38.430
was doing and what it was
capable of, you have to

00:21:38.430 --> 00:21:42.490
remember that the browser share
that actually supported

00:21:42.490 --> 00:21:43.990
HTML5 was actually pretty low.

00:21:43.990 --> 00:21:46.060
And game developers of that time
were very much concerned

00:21:46.060 --> 00:21:46.650
about reach.

00:21:46.650 --> 00:21:50.590
I mean, we're talking about late
2008, early 2009, when

00:21:50.590 --> 00:21:53.540
the big thing to do was to write
a Flash game and put it

00:21:53.540 --> 00:21:54.920
on a social network.

00:21:54.920 --> 00:21:57.460
So you were more concerned
with daily active users

00:21:57.460 --> 00:21:59.780
clicking your pink cow than
you were anything else.

00:21:59.780 --> 00:22:01.890
So fast-forward to 2012.

00:22:01.890 --> 00:22:03.060
We've now got--

00:22:03.060 --> 00:22:07.600
the dominant share of users
can run HTML5 games.

00:22:07.600 --> 00:22:09.280
The problem now is
that the focus is

00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:10.620
in a different medium.

00:22:10.620 --> 00:22:13.400
The focus is in mobile and
what mobile is doing.

00:22:13.400 --> 00:22:16.910
We did a great thing for
Google I/O this year.

00:22:16.910 --> 00:22:19.490
We actually took some game
developers, or some ex-game

00:22:19.490 --> 00:22:21.830
developers who work at Google,
and we made a game.

00:22:21.830 --> 00:22:24.330
We said, let's figure out if
this HTML5 thing is actually

00:22:24.330 --> 00:22:24.860
worth the hype.

00:22:24.860 --> 00:22:27.840
We made a game called Grits,
which is a top-down 2D

00:22:27.840 --> 00:22:29.750
shooter, and you could actually
just Google for my

00:22:29.750 --> 00:22:31.870
name and the word Grits and
you'll find everything.

00:22:31.870 --> 00:22:34.480
But we actually took a look at
it and said, we're ex-game

00:22:34.480 --> 00:22:34.950
developers.

00:22:34.950 --> 00:22:36.690
Let's approach HTML5 and
figure out if it's

00:22:36.690 --> 00:22:37.590
hype or if it's not.

00:22:37.590 --> 00:22:41.120
And what we found was this, was
that people approaching

00:22:41.120 --> 00:22:45.090
HTML5 development have
two skewed views.

00:22:45.090 --> 00:22:47.360
Number one, they think
it's in a vacuum.

00:22:47.360 --> 00:22:49.890
They believe that HTML5
development is its own little

00:22:49.890 --> 00:22:52.240
island and no one's ever
made games before.

00:22:52.240 --> 00:22:55.670
Like, the people we talked to
were completely oblivious to

00:22:55.670 --> 00:22:59.880
very good tools, like
TexturePacker or Tiled.

00:22:59.880 --> 00:23:02.140
These are staples of 2D
game development.

00:23:02.140 --> 00:23:04.200
The people in the HTML5 world,
or even the Web world, just

00:23:04.200 --> 00:23:05.260
didn't know.

00:23:05.260 --> 00:23:07.010
They're coming from the world
where they're expecting this

00:23:07.010 --> 00:23:09.160
IDE that Flash has,
and expecting

00:23:09.160 --> 00:23:10.830
something to migrate over.

00:23:10.830 --> 00:23:13.200
So that was first an issue, in
sort of educating people that

00:23:13.200 --> 00:23:14.910
hey, listen, it's all data.

00:23:14.910 --> 00:23:17.230
If you export a 3D model
from Maya, you

00:23:17.230 --> 00:23:18.480
can load it in WebGL.

00:23:18.480 --> 00:23:20.540
It's just data.

00:23:20.540 --> 00:23:23.700
The second problem was that
developers were sort of

00:23:23.700 --> 00:23:28.650
approaching the HTML5 concept
from a very different

00:23:28.650 --> 00:23:31.570
viewpoint, which was that they
thought it should all be

00:23:31.570 --> 00:23:33.630
integrated and all solve
every problem,

00:23:33.630 --> 00:23:34.680
everywhere, at every time.

00:23:34.680 --> 00:23:36.760
Which kind of is due to the
hyperbolic nature of the

00:23:36.760 --> 00:23:37.270
statements.

00:23:37.270 --> 00:23:40.880
But what we've really found is
that HTML5 is a Web language.

00:23:40.880 --> 00:23:42.430
It was designed for
the internet.

00:23:42.430 --> 00:23:44.910
Believe it or not, it wasn't
actually designed for games.

00:23:44.910 --> 00:23:48.620
What we've been able to do is,
because HTML5 is so powerful,

00:23:48.620 --> 00:23:50.890
we've been able to do
gaming experiences.

00:23:50.890 --> 00:23:53.700
Well, this comes to the tier
of like, what the demo John

00:23:53.700 --> 00:23:56.370
showed and everything, which is
that HTML5 is great for a

00:23:56.370 --> 00:23:57.500
tier of experiences.

00:23:57.500 --> 00:23:59.200
When you want to move beyond
that tier, you're going to

00:23:59.200 --> 00:24:00.370
quickly run into problems.

00:24:00.370 --> 00:24:02.680
And my talk, I talk about
that, I won't go into it

00:24:02.680 --> 00:24:04.750
today, but when you hit that
tier you're going to say, hey,

00:24:04.750 --> 00:24:07.750
you know what, there's certain
things that we just cannot do.

00:24:07.750 --> 00:24:09.380
It's like dealing with limited
hardware right?

00:24:09.380 --> 00:24:12.780
You're not going to be able to
render 2.4 million polygons on

00:24:12.780 --> 00:24:13.930
your mobile device today.

00:24:13.930 --> 00:24:14.980
It just doesn't work.

00:24:14.980 --> 00:24:17.080
So it's a tier of
applications.

00:24:17.080 --> 00:24:18.650
Once you hit that point, you've
got to move forwards.

00:24:18.650 --> 00:24:21.520
So I believe the future of HTML5
is very bright, I'm very

00:24:21.520 --> 00:24:23.930
encouraged about it, but I think
the problem has been

00:24:23.930 --> 00:24:24.990
messaging, to this point.

00:24:24.990 --> 00:24:26.020
It's been very hyperbolic.

00:24:26.020 --> 00:24:29.870
It hasn't been very pragmatic
about what game developers

00:24:29.870 --> 00:24:30.980
should actually be doing.

